            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Here are the bits of the ada runtime that are causing this:\r\n```\r\nfunction GetAdaIndent()\r\n   exe 'normal! $F)%'\r\n   return 6\r\nendfunction GetAdaIndent\r\nsetlocal indentexpr=GetAdaIndent()\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo the problem here is that:\r\n\r\n1) Neovim enters insert mode to do the formatting.\r\n2) This [overwrites the global State](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/52397aaa0d1e2d4ce1320c73761cf316fc608ffb/src/nvim/ops.c#L4315).\r\n3) [insertchar](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/52397aaa0d1e2d4ce1320c73761cf316fc608ffb/src/nvim/ops.c#L4318) calls [internal_format](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/52397aaa0d1e2d4ce1320c73761cf316fc608ffb/src/nvim/edit.c#L5628) which calls [open_line](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/master/src/nvim/edit.c#L6089) which calls [do_c_expr_indent](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/52397aaa0d1e2d4ce1320c73761cf316fc608ffb/src/nvim/change.c#L1750).\r\n4) When the indentexpr is called, `exe normal!` results in a call to [save_current_state](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/52397aaa0d1e2d4ce1320c73761cf316fc608ffb/src/nvim/ex_docmd.c#L8404) and then [restore_current_state](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/52397aaa0d1e2d4ce1320c73761cf316fc608ffb/src/nvim/ex_docmd.c#L8423), which makes a call to [ui_cursor_shape](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/52397aaa0d1e2d4ce1320c73761cf316fc608ffb/src/nvim/ex_docmd.c#L8347). Cursor shape turns into a bar.\r\n5) ui_cursor_shape is never called again. Sadness ensues.\r\n\r\nTo me it sounds like the best solution would be to use save_current_state at the beginning and restore_current_state at the end of either do_pending_operator, op_format or format_lines.\r\n\r\n@bfredl Sorry to bother you but I don't know if anybody's more knowledgeable than you about this state business, what would be the best solution in your opinion?\r\n\r\nBtw I used [pernosco](https://pernos.co/debug/lKGkf0nDCTK7K9MTskr2Bg/index.html#f{m[Ek4,Afdg_,t[AQ,AqtK_,f{e[Ek4,k/4_,s{aVhPE2UAA,bBA,uFYUW,oFa+F___) to figure out what was going on and I must say this is the best debugger I've ever had the chance to use. I highly recommend it (despite its very high price).",
